  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant penalties. The specific penalties depend on the statute under which the individual is charged, but generally include the following:\n\n### **1. Criminal Penalties:**\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** (Laundering of Monetary Instruments):  \n     - **Fine**: Up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.  \n     - **Imprisonment**: Up to 20 years per count.  \n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** (Engaging in Monetary Transactions in Property Derived from Specified Unlawful Activity):  \n     - **Fine**: Up to $250,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.  \n     - **Imprisonment**: Up to 10 years per count.  \n\n### **2. Civil Penalties:**\n   - Civil penalties can include fines up to the value of the laundered funds or property involved in the transaction.  \n   - Assets involved in money laundering may also be subject to forfeiture under federal law.\n\n### **3. Enhanced Penalties:**\n   - If the money laundering involves proceeds from certain high-level criminal activities (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, or other serious offenses), additional penalties may apply, including longer prison sentences and higher fines.  \n   - Repeat offenders may face enhanced penalties.\n\n### **4. Additional Consequences:**\n   - **Asset Forfeiture**: The government can seize property, funds, or assets linked to the money laundering scheme.  \n   - **Restitution**: Courts may order the defendant to repay victims or entities harmed by the money laundering activity.  \n   - **Collateral Consequences**: Convictions for money laundering can result in loss of professional licenses, difficulty obtaining employment, and damage to reputation.\n\n### **5. Conspiracy and Attempt:**\n   - Conspiring to commit money laundering or attempting to do so can result in the same penalties as actually completing the offense.\n\nThese penalties reflect the federal government\u2019s commitment to combating financial crimes and the serious nature of money laundering offenses. If charged with money laundering, individuals should seek legal counsel to understand their rights and defenses.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
